^?Introduction to the UNIX Desktop
^0^UNIX SVR4.2
^$10
UNIX SVR4.2

UNIX SVR4.2 is a new version of UNIX System V which supports an
easy-to-use graphical user interface, known as the \k(UNIX Desktop).
With UNIX SVR4.2 you simply click the mouse to do tasks that invoke
UNIX System commands.

Related Documents:

   o Reference Cards: A set of quick reference cards are located at the
     back of Mastering the UNIX Desktop. They provide a quick reminder
     on how to use the mouse, keyboard, windows, and other components
     of the UNIX Desktop.

   o UNIX Desktop Quick Startup: If you have never used a graphical
     product such as the UNIX Desktop, we suggest you go through the
     UNIX Desktop Quick Startup. It provides simple tasks to help fam-
     iliarize you with the UNIX Desktop.
^1^UNIX Desktop
^$20
\k{UNIX SVR4.2}
1. UNIX Desktop

The UNIX Desktop is where you do your work. It comprises your entire
screen and contains \k(windows^^Windows), \k(icons^^Icons), and \k(menus^^Menus). To use the Desktop
effectively a \k(mouse^^Using the Mouse) should be used.

The \k(UNIX Desktop window^^UNIX Desktop Window) appears when you first start UNIX SVR4.2.
It provides access to the files, applications, and other features that
make up the Desktop.

To open one of the icons, position the mouse pointer over the icon and
\d(Double-click^double-click) the SELECT (left) mouse button.
^2^Using the Mouse
^$30
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 Using the Mouse

A mouse is a hand-held pointing device used to:

   o manipulate icons and windows

   o display and select items from UNIX Desktop menus.

By moving the mouse across the Desktop and pressing the mouse buttons
you can open folders, run applications, move files, and more. To use
your mouse:

  1. Hold the mouse in the palm of your hand with your fingers near
     the mouse buttons. The cord connecting the mouse to your computer
     should point away from you.

  2. Move your mouse around on a mouse pad or a clear desk top. The
     mouse pointer move on the screen as you move the mouse.

  3. When the mouse pointer is over items on the desktop, such as
     icons or windows, you use the mouse buttons to act on the items.

The SELECT (left) mouse button is used most often. With it you can
\d(drag-and-drop) and open icons.

Note that you do not need a mouse to use UNIX Desktop but it is highly
recommended. See the Advanced Navigation Reference Cards at the back
of the Mastering the UNIX Desktop for more information on
keyboard navigation.

More information:

        \k(Mouse Types)
        \k(Mouse Buttons)
        \k(Starting Applications with the Mouse)
^3^Mouse Types
^$40
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.1 Mouse Types

There are several different types of mice supported by UNIX SVR4.2.
They are distinguished by:

   o Type of Mouse: With the UNIX Desktop, you can use either a Bus,
     PS2, or Serial mouse.

   o Number of mouse buttons: The UNIX Desktop works with both two-
     and three-button mice.
^3^Mouse Buttons
^$50
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 Mouse Buttons

Different functions are attached to each mouse button. To get some
functions you have to hold down keys from the keyboard while you press
mouse buttons.

There are several major functions associated clicking your mouse buttons:

   o \k(SELECT)

   o \k(ADJUST/Toggle)

   o \k(PASTE)

   o \k(MENU)

   o \k(Other Mouse Functions)

Some of these functions are activated differently for two- and three-
button mice. For some functions you must use the Control (Ctrl) and/or
the Shift keys:

\tTwo-button mouse\t\t\tThree-button mouse
\t==================\t\t\t===================

SELECT\tLeft mouse button\t\t\tLeft mouse button

ADJUST\tShift-Left mouse button\t\tCtrl-Left mouse button

PASTE\tRight mouse button\t\t\tMiddle mouse button

MENU\tShift-Ctrl-Left mouse button\t\tRight mouse button

To use the Ctrl and Shift keys with a mouse button, first press and
hold the indicated key(s) and then click the appropriate mouse button.

The UNIX Desktop help uses shorthand conventions to indicate which
mouse buttons you should to press. For example, you might be instructed
to click on a window button or menu item. This means use the Left
mouse button (both two- and three-button mice). Or, you might be
instructed to click MENU on an object. You would use Shift-Ctrl-Left
mouse button (as shown above) with a two-button mouse or use the
Right mouse button on a three-button mouse.
^4^SELECT
^$60
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.1 SELECT

The SELECT mouse function is used for most UNIX Desktop operations.
With the SELECT mouse button, you can:

   o Change the active input focus from one window to another:

     Active input focus refers to the area of the screen that accepts
     input from the keyboard. To give a window active input focus,
     click on either the header or one of the window's borders (move
     the pointer to the header or border and click the SELECT mouse
     button). When a window has active input focus, any characters you
     type automatically go to the application running in the window.

     Example: \k(Changing Active Input Focus)

   o Operate a menu bar or menu item:

     When you click on a menu bar item, a menu appears. When you click
     on an item in the menu, one of several things may happen:

     - If the menu item is followed by three dots (...) then a popup
       window opens.

     - If the menu item is followed by an arrow, then a submenu
       appears.

     - If the menu item is not followed by anything, then the action
       indicated by the menu item is performed.

     Example: \k(Operating a Menu Button and Menu Item)

   o Select controls:

     Clicking on a control, such as a button, causes the control to
     perform its designated function.

     Example: \k(Selecting Controls)

   o Increase or decrease the size of a window:

     To change the size of a window, drag a window's resize corner or
     border until the window is the desired size (that is, point to a
     resize corner or border and press the SELECT mouse button while
     dragging the resize corner or border, then release the SELECT mouse
     button).

     Example: \k(Increasing and Decreasing the Size of a Window)

   o Move a window or an icon:

     To move a window, drag the window's title bar until the window is
     at the desired location (that is, press the SELECT mouse button
     on the window's title bar, drag the window to the new location
     and release the SELECT mouse button. Press the SELECT mouse but-
     ton on any part of an icon to drag it to a new location.

     Example: \k(Moving a Window)

   o Selecting an Object

     Click on an icon inside a Folder Window on which you want to per-
     form file management commands.

     Example: \k(Selecting an Object)

   o Selecting Multiple Files:

     With the mouse pointer in a Folder Window, press and hold SELECT
     and drag the mouse pointer across several icons. This creates a
     bounding box that stretches around the icons. All icons that are
     completely enclosed in the bounding box are selected. Once
     selected, you can act on all the icons together. You can also
     select multiple files by using the \k(ADJUST^^ADJUST/Toggle) button.

     Example: \k(Selecting Multiple Files)
^4^Changing Active Input Focus
^$70
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.2 Changing Active Input Focus

Here is an example of changing the active input focus:

  1. \d(Double-click^double-click) on the Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.
     The Applications window is now active and the header and borders
     are highlighted differently than the UNIX Desktop window.

  2. In the Applications window \d(double-click^double-click) SELECT on the Text
     Editor icon. The Text Editor window opens and is now active. The
     header and borders are highlighted differently than the
     Application and UNIX Desktop windows. While the Text Editor
     window is active you can type in it.

  3. Click on the Applications or UNIX Desktop window header and
     type. You can no longer type in the Text Editor Window.

  4. Click on the Text Editor window header and once again you can
     type in it.

  5. To close the Text Editor window, click on the File button and
     then click on the Exit menu item.
^4^Operating a Menu Button and Menu Item
^$80
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.3 Operating a Menu Button and Menu Item

Here is an example of operating the menu bar and menu items:

  1. If the Applications window is not already open, \d(double-click^double-click) on the
     Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.

  2. Click on View in the menu bar, that is, place the mouse pointer
     on View in the Applications window menu bar and click the SELECT
     mouse button. A menu appears.

  3. Click on the Sort menu item. A submenu appears.

  4. Click on Name. The menus disappear and the icons in the window
     are sorted by their name.
^4^Selecting Controls
^$90
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.4 Selecting Controls

Here is an example of Selecting controls:

  1. If the Applications window is not already open, \d(double-click^double-click) on the
     Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.

  2. In the Applications window \d(double-click^double-click) on the Text Editor icon.
     The Text Editor window opens.

  3. Click on File in the menu bar. A menu appears.

  4. Click on Exit from the menu. You have just selected a control
     from a menu. This causes a function to be carried out. The Editor
     window closes.
^4^Increasing and Decreasing the Size of a Window
^$100
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.5 Increasing and Decreasing the Size of a Window

Here is an example of increasing and decreasing the size of a window:

  1. You can use any of the windows open on the Desktop for this
     example. Move the mouse pointer over any corner of a window and
     note how the mouse pointer changes to an arrow and right angle
     symbol. Move the pointer over any side and note how the mouse
     pointer changes to an arrow and straight line.

  2. With the mouse pointer over a side or a corner, press and hold
     the SELECT mouse button.

  3. Move the mouse and note how the boundary of the window moves.
     You can make the window either smaller or larger.

  4. Release the mouse button when the window is the size you want.
^4^Moving a Window
^$110
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.6 Moving a Window

Here is an Example of moving a window around the Desktop:

  1. You can use any of the windows open on the Desktop for this
     example. Place the pointer on the title area of a window.

  2. Press and hold the SELECT mouse button.

  3. Move your mouse and note that the frame of the window moves
     with it.

  4. Release the SELECT mouse button and the window is moved to the
     new location of the Desktop.
^4^Selecting an Object
^$120
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.7 Selecting an Object

Here is an Example of Selecting an object:

  1. If the Applications window is not already open, \d(double-click^double-click) on the
     Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.

  2. In the Applications window, click on the clock.

  3. The word clock icon becomes highlighted and is now selected.
^4^Selecting Multiple Files
^$130
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.8 Selecting Multiple Files

Here is an Example of Selecting multiple files:

  1. To select all the icons in the Applications window, place the mouse
     pointer in the upper left corner of the window, but not on an icon.

  2. Press and hold the SELECT mouse button.

  3. Drag the mouse pointer and a dotted frame (bounding box)
     appears. Enclose all the icons in this frame and release the
     SELECT button.

  4. All the icons that were completely enclosed by the bounding
     box are selected.

  5. To return to only one selected icon, click on an icon.
^4^ADJUST/Toggle
^$140
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.9 ADJUST/Toggle

ADJUST is used to make multiple selections and is useful when you want
to select two or more icon that are not located next to each other.
For example, you can use the ADJUST function to select three file
icons in a Folder window, then open all three files (using the Open
selection under the File button).

Example: \k(Using the ADJUST Function)
^4^Using the ADJUST Function
^$150
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.10 Using the ADJUST Function

  1. In the UNIX Desktop window, click on any icon.

  2. Click ADJUST (Ctrl + SELECT for both two- and three-button
     mice) on any other icon and note that both icons are selected.

  3. Repeat Step 2 on any number of icons.

  4. To unselect the icons, click on any one icon. All the icons
     except the one just selected are now unselected.
^4^PASTE
^$160
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.11 PASTE

Paste is used for text only. It lets you quickly copy a section of
text from one window to another, or from one location to another
inside the same window. To use Paste:

  1. Select text in one window (move the mouse pointer over the
     text while pressing SELECT).

  2. Move the mouse pointer to another window or different location
     in the same window.

  3. Click PASTE (Right button on two-button mice and Middle button
     on three-button mice). The selected text is copied to the mouse
     pointer location.
^4^MENU
^$170
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.12 MENU

MENU is used to bring up a menu for an item. With the mouse pointer on
a window menu button, a window button or an icon, click MENU to bring
up a menu of functions for that item. You can then click on one of the
menu items.

Example: \k(Using the MENU Function)
^4^Using the MENU Function
^$180
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.13 Using the MENU Function

Here is an example of using the Menu function:

  1. If the Applications window is not already open, \d(double-click^double-click) on the
     Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.

  2. Click MENU (Shift + Ctrl + SELECT on two-button mice and the
     Right button on three-button mice) with the mouse pointer on the
     Clock icon. A popup menu appears.

  3. Click on Open.

  4. The Clock opens.

  5. To remove the clock click the MENU button on the Window menu
     button (upper left-hand corner). The window menu appears. Click
     on Close.
^4^Other Mouse Functions
^$190
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.2 \k{Mouse Buttons}
             1.1.2.14 Other Mouse Functions

Using different mouse modifiers (keystrokes along with mouse buttons)
you can perform other functions with your mouse, such as Copy, Link,
and Move (see below), as well as several others. Not all of these
functions are available in all windows.

   o Copy: To copy an icon from one window to another, hold down the
     ALT key and SELECT mouse button while dragging the icon.

   o Link: To link an icon from one window to another, hold down the
     Ctrl and Alt keys and SELECT mouse button while dragging the
     icon.

   o Move: To move an icon from one window to another, just use the
     SELECT mouse button while dragging the icon.

See the Basic Navigation Reference Cards at the back of the Mastering
the UNIX Desktop for information on additional mouse functions.
^3^Starting Applications with the Mouse
^$200
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.1 \k{Using the Mouse}
       1.1.3 Starting Applications with the Mouse

Starting Applications with the Mouse

To start an application with the mouse, first locate the application's
icon in a window. Next, move the mouse pointer over the icon and
\d(double-click^double-click) the SELECT mouse button. The following example
shows how to start up the Puzzle application.

  1. If the Applications window is not already open, \d(double-click^double-click) on the
     Applications icon in the UNIX Desktop Window.

  2. Move the mouse pointer to the Puzzle icon and \d(double-click^double-click) the
     SELECT mouse button. The Puzzle window appears.

  3. Click SELECT on a numbered square adjacent to the blank square
     to move it to the blank position. You can click on the Solve but-
     ton to let the system solve the puzzle for you.

  4. When you are done playing, click on the Window Menu button and
     then click on Close.
^2^UNIX Desktop Window
^$210
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 UNIX Desktop Window

The UNIX Desktop window provides access to the major system features,
including:

        \k(Applications Folder)
        \k(Disks-etc Folder)
        \k(Folder Map)
        \k(Help Desk)
        \k(Mailbox Folder)
        \k(Preferences Folder)
        \k(Shutdown)
        \k(System Setup Folder)
        \k(Utilities Folder)
        \k(UUCP Inbox Folder)
        \k(Wastebasket)
^3^Applications Folder
^$220
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.1 Applications Folder

The Applications Folder contains the applications that come with UNIX
SVE4.2. They include: Calculator, Clock, Text Editor, Mail, Terminal,
and Puzzle. This would be a good place to store your own applications
so they would be grouped in one convenient location.
^3^Disks-etc Folder
^$230
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.2 Disks-etc Folder

The Disks-etc Folder is where you access your cartridge tape and
floppy disk drives. These would be used for backing up and restoring
files or loading new software or files onto your system.
^3^Folder Map
^$240
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.3 Folder Map

The Folder Map shows a graphical representation of your folders.
Folder are connected by lines to show their relationships, that is,
which folders are contained in other folders.
^3^Help Desk
^$250
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.4 Help Desk

The Help Desk contains icons that provide access to on-line help for
all of the facilities available in the UNIX Desktop.
^3^Mailbox Folder
^$260
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.5 Mailbox Folder

The Mailbox Folder is where your incoming mail messages are kept.
Also, when you save mail, it is saved to a file in this folder unless
you specify a different folder at the time you save the message.
^3^Preferences Folder
^$270
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.6 Preferences Folder

The Preferences Folder provides access to icons that let you change
the characteristics of your Desktop. For example, you can change the
colors, icon definitions, mouse usage, keyboard mappings, and various
other characteristics.
^3^Shutdown
^$280
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.7 Shutdown

Shutdown must be used when you want to restart or turn off your system.
^3^System Setup Folder
^$290
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.8 System Setup Folder

The System Setup folder contains applications for setting up basic
system services. These include Application Setup, Dialup Setup, Font
Setup, File Sharing, Icon Setup, Internet Setup, Password Setup,
Printer Setup, User Setup, and Advanced Administration.
^3^Utilities Folder
^$300
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.9 Utilities Folder

The Utilities Folder contains utilities for maintaining your system,
such as Backup Restore, Pixmap Editor, System Status, and Task
Scheduler.
^3^UUCP Inbox Folder
^$310
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.10 UUCP Folder

The UUCP Folder contains files sent to you, using the UUCP facility,
from remote systems.
^3^Wastebasket
^$320
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.2 \k{UNIX Desktop Window}
       1.2.11 Wastebasket

The Wastebasket is where deleted files go temporarily before they are
permanently deleted. You can retrieve deleted files from the
Wastebasket until a set time is reached or until they are explicitly
deleted by you.
^2^Windows
^$330
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 Windows

A Window is a rectangle on the Desktop that is associated with a par-
ticular application. The parts of a window are:

        \k(Title Bar)
        \k(Window Menu Button)
        \k(Minimize Button)
        \k(Maximize Button)
        \k(Menu Bar)
        \k(Pane)
        \k(Footer)
        \k(Scrollbar)
        \k(Resize Corners^^Resize Corners and Edges)
        \k(Borders)
^3^Title Bar
^$340
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.1 Title Bar

The Title Bar spans the top of a window and contains the window's
title. For example, the Title Area of the UNIX Desktop window says
"UNIX Desktop - your_login_ID." Click on the Title Bar to make a
window active.
^3^Window Menu Button
^$350
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.2 Window Menu Button

To the left of the Title Bar is a box, containing a horizontal bar, called
the Window Menu button. Clicking on this button brings up the window
menu containing basic window functions, such as \k(Restore), \k(Move),
\k(Size), \k(Minimize), \k(Maximize), \k(Lower), and \k(Close). Note that not all menu
functions are always active and some windows do not have the Minimize,
Maximize, Size, or Restore functions.
^3^Minimize Button
^$360
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.3 Minimize Button

To the right of the Title Bar is a box, containing a small square, called
the Minimize button. Clicking on this box reduces the window to
an \d(Active Icon).
^3^Maximize Button
^$370
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.4 Maximize Button

To the right of the Minimize button is the Maximize Button. Clicking
on this button causes the window to expand and occupy your entire
screen. If a window is already Maximized when you click on this but-
ton, the window reverts back to the size it was before it was Maxim-
ized.
^3^Menu Bar
^$380
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.5 Menu Bar

Below the Title Area is the menu bar. This is used for initiating actions
either on the window or its contents. For example, in the UNIX Desktop
window, the menu bar provides access to the File, View, Edit, Folders,
and Help menus.
^3^Pane
^$390
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.6 Pane

The central part of the window, where you perform your work, is the Pane.
The UNIX Desktop window pane contains icons such as Preferences, System
Setup, Applications, and so on.
^3^Footer
^$400
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.7 Footer

Below the Pane is the Footer area. Information and error messages are
displayed in this area. For example, the UNIX Desktop window shows the
total number of items in the window and how many are selected.
^3^Scrollbar
^$410
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.8 Scrollbar

When a window is too small to show all of its contents, a scrollbar
appears. It could be a horizontal scrollbar, vertical scrollbar, or both.
They are used to move the view of the pane so you can see the rest
of the contents of the window. To use the scrollbar, press the SELECT
(left) button when the mouse pointer is over the slider (the box in
the center of the scrollbar) and drag it until what you want is in
view. You can also click on the arrows on either end of the scrollbar
to make the pane move in small steps.
^3^Resize Corners and Edges
^$420
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.9 Resize Corners

At each corner of a main window is a resize corner.  You can expand
and shrink a window by dragging the resize corners (while pressing the
SELECT mouse button). Note that some windows do not have resize
corners.

^3^Borders
^$430
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.3 \k{Windows}
       1.3.10 Borders

On the four sides of a window are borders.

In main windows, these borders can be dragged to resize the window
(like \k(resize corners^^Resize Corners and Edges)). Some windows, known as pop-up windows,
typically have borders that cannot be used for resizing.
^2^Icons
^$440
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.4 Icons

Icons are pictorial representations of applications, files, or folders
and are located either inside windows or on the Desktop. Icons inside
windows represent files and folders that are closed or applications
you have not yet started. Icons on the Desktop are known as Active
Icons. Active Icons represent files and folders that are open or
applications that are running. Active Icons are usually located at the
bottom of the Desktop.

More information:

        \k(Icons in a Window)
        \k(Active Icons)
^3^Icons in a Window
^$450
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.4 \k{Icons}
       1.4.1 Icons in a Window

Icons inside windows are used to represent many different elements.
For example, an icon can represent:

   o a data file.

   o a folder containing files and other folders.

   o a device such as a printer, tape drive or floppy diskette drive.

   o a remote system, to which you can send files or share resources.

There are several ways to use the icons inside windows. You can
\d(double-click^double-click) SELECT on an icon to open it. What happens depends
on the type of icon:

   o Text File - The text editor application is started with the file
     ready for editing.

   o Other Data File - If the data file is known by the system to be
     associated with a particular application, that application starts
     with this file open in the application.

   o Application - The application is started.

   o Folder - The folder is opened, displaying its contents.

You can find out more about an icon by looking at its properties. To
view the properties of an icon:

  1. Click MENU on the icon. Its menu appears.

     For a two-button mouse press Ctrl + Shift + left mouse button.
     For A three-button mouse press the right mouse button.

  2. Click on Properties from the menu (move the mouse pointer to
     the Properties and click the SELECT mouse button).

     The Properties sheet shows who owns the file, the read/write
     /execute permission of the file, and when it was last modified.
^3^Active Icons
^$460
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.4 \k{Icons}
       1.4.2 Active Icons

To avoid having many widows cluttering your desktop, you can close
windows temporarily without stopping what's going on in the window.
The effect is to reduce the window to a small icon, know as an Active
Icon, that aligns itself neatly along the bottom of the Desktop.

To reduce a window to an Active Icon, do the following:

  1. Move the mouse pointer to the minimize button (the box con-
     taining the small square in the upper right-hand corner of the
     window.

  2. Click the SELECT mouse button.

To restore an Active Icon to a window, do the following:

  1. Move the mouse pointer to the icon.

  2. Click the SELECT mouse button to make the menu appear. Click
     on Restore from the menu (click the SELECT mouse button on it).
     You can also \d(double-click) on an Active Icon as a quick way to
     open it.

More information: \k(Menus)
^2^Menus
^$470
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 Menus

A menu is a list of items that pops up when you select an item from
the menu bar. The menu gives you a choice of actions or settings. For
example, every folder window has a Window Menu button in the corner to
the left of the window title bar. Clicking on this button brings up a
menu with the following options (also, selecting an \k(Active Icon^^Icons) brings
up this menu):

   o \k(Restore)

   o \k(Move)

   o \k(Size)

   o \k(Minimize)

   o \k(Maximize)

   o \k(Lower)

   o \k(Close)

These are the actions you can perform on a window (or Active Icon).
Note that some menu items may be dimmed. Only the menu items that
are not dimmed can be selected. Clicking on a dimmed menu item has
no effect.
^3^Restore
^$480
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.1 Restore

Restore has two functions. First, it restores Active Icons to windows.
Second, it reduces a \k(maximized^^Maximize) window to its original window size.
^3^Move
^$490
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.2 Move

Move lets you move a window or \k(Active Icon^^Icons) around the Desktop. Clicking
on Move changes the mouse pointer into four arrows, pointing up, down,
left, and right. When you move the mouse, the window or icon moves
with it. Click SELECT to place the window or icon in its new
location.
^3^Size
^$500
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.3 Size

Size is only active for main windows. It lets you resize a window.
Clicking on Size changes the mouse pointer into four arrows, pointing
up, down, left, and right. When you move the mouse pointer past either
a corner or border (including the top and bottom) that part expands or
shrinks as you move the mouse. Click SELECT when the window is the
size you want.
^3^Minimize
^$510
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.4 Minimize

Minimize is only active for main windows. Minimize reduces a window to
an \k(Active Icon^^Icons).
^3^Maximize
^$520
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.5 Maximize

Maximize creates a full screen size window from either a smaller main
window or \k(Active Icon^^Icons). Use \k(Restore) to reduce a maximized window to
its original size.
^3^Lower
^$530
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.6 Lower

Lower moves either a window or \k(Active Icon^^Icons) below (sometimes referred to
as behind) other windows and icons on the Desktop. To bring a window
to the surface (on top of other windows and Active Icons), click on its
border or title area. To bring an Active Icon to the surface, click
anywhere on the icon.
^3^Close
^$540
1. \k{UNIX Desktop}
   1.5 \k{Menus}
       1.5.7 Close

Close "removes" the window or \k(Active Icon^^Icons) from the Desktop. The application
associated with the window may be re-started by double-clicking on its
icon (either in the UNIX Desktop window or other folder window). If
you try to Close the UNIX Desktop window, a Notice window appears
warning your that this ends your Desktop session.
^1^Help
^$550
\k{UNIX SVR4.2}
2. Help

On-line help is available for the windows and applications that come
with UNIX SVR4.2. The on-line help is a hypertext-based system that
provides detailed information and lets you navigate the various help
topics by selecting special words, called links. When you click on a link,
the current text in the help window is replaced by text describing
the topic associated with the link.

There are four ways to access on-line help:

        \k(Help Menu)
        \k(Help Button)
        \k(Help Desk)
        \k(Help Key)
^2^Help Menu
^$560
2. \k{Help}
   2.1 Help Menu

Clicking on Help in a window's menu bar pops up the help menu. Click-
ing on the first item on the help menu brings up on-line help for that
window.
^2^Help Button
^$570
2. \k{Help}
   2.2 Help Button

Some windows contain a Help button. Clicking on the Help button brings
up on-line help for that window.
^2^Help Desk
^$580
2. \k{Help}

   2.3 Help Desk

The Help Desk contains icons for UNIX SVR4.2 Applications. Click on an
icon to see a short description of that application at the bottom of
the window. Double-click on the icon to bring up the application's
on-line help.

The Help Desk is accessed either from the menu brought up by the Help
button or from the Help Desk icon in the UNIX Desktop window.
^2^Help Key
^$590
2. \k{Help}
   2.4 Help Key

Move the mouse pointer over the object you want help on. Now press the
Help key (the F1 key).

More information: \k(Help Window^DesktopMgr/help.hlp^Help)
