^$600
\k{UNIX SVR4.2}
3. Using the UNIX Desktop

To use the UNIX Desktop you must know how to perform some basic
operations, like starting and stopping your system and using the mouse
and keyboard.

        \k(Starting Up)
        \k(Shutting Down)
        \k(Using the Mouse)
^2^Starting Up
^$610
3. \k{Using the UNIX Desktop}
   3.1 Starting Up

This procedure details how to start your UNIX SVR4.2 system.

  1. Turn on the Power:

     Turn on the power switch to your computer and monitor. If UNIX
     SVR4.2 has been properly installed, after a short time you should
     see the login window.

  2. Enter your login ID:

     Type in your login ID and press Enter. (A login should have been
     created for you when your system was installed.) You are prompted
     for a password

      Password:

  3. Enter your password:

     If this is not the first time you are logging to your system, go
     to Step 4.

     If this is your first time logging in to your system after load-
     ing UNIX SVR4.2, you have no password; press Enter for
     your password. You are now prompted for a new password.

     Type in a word or phrase containing more then 6 characters and
     press Enter. There must be at least two alphabetic and one
     numeric or special character included in your password and it
     must differ with your login. Your password is not displayed as
     you type. You are prompted to re-enter you new password to
     confirm that you have entered it correctly.

     Type in exactly what you typed in for your new password and press
     Enter. Your password is not displayed on your monitor as you
     type.

  4. Enter your password:

     If this is your first time logging in, go back to step 3. Otherwise,
     type in your password and press Enter. Your password is not
     displayed as you type. If you do not enter your login or password
     correctly, you are not logged into the system. The login prompt
     appears again. Try Entering you login ID and password again,
     until you successfully log in.

Once you have successfully logged in, the UNIX Desktop appears and is
ready for use. You can use the mouse and keyboard to run applications
or maintain your system.
^2^Shutting Down
^$620
3. \k{Using the UNIX Desktop}
   3.2 Shutting Down

Never just turn off your computer! Unlike less powerful computer
operating systems, there is always something happening on a UNIX
SVR4.2 system. Processes are running to monitor your computer, check
for programs waiting to run, and listen for incoming calls from the
network.

If you just turn off your system, you could lose data or damage some
of your system files so that the system doesn't work properly next
time you start it. Instead, when ever you want to turn off your com-
puter, do the following.

  1. Save all files you have been working on. Quit all applications
     properly.

  2. \d(Double-click^double-click) the SELECT (left) mouse button on the Shutdown
     icon from the UNIX Desktop window.(If the Shutdown icon is not
     available, go to Step 4.)

  3. Click on one of the following buttons from the Exit Notice
     window:

     - Save Session and Exit Button - The Save Session and Exit button
       remembers the position of the windows and icons on your desktop.
       The next time you log in, they are returned to their positions.

     - Exit Button - The Exit button lets you exit the desktop without
       saving the current session.

     - Cancel Button- The Cancel button cancels your request to exit
       the Desktop. After selecting Cancel, you can continue working
       on the Desktop.

     - Help Button - The Help button provides on-line help for the
       Exit Notice.

     If you select the Save Session and Exit or Exit button, the system
     stops after a few moments. When you see the message, "Reboot the
     computer now," you can safely turn off the power.

  4. If the Shutdown icon is not available, open the UNIX Desktop
     window if it's not already opened. Click on the File button.
     A pop-up menu appears. Click on Exit Desktop. Continue with
     Step 3.
